Appendix A — Annotated Evidence Foundation
Purpose of This Appendix
This appendix records the principal evidence sources currently connected to the design of the HCOS™ Healthcare Instruments described in this document.
The presence of a source in this appendix means that it informs a concept, boundary, safeguard, or design question. It does not mean that the source validates an HCOS™ instrument, establishes clinical effectiveness, or authorizes independent decision-making.
Each annotation separates:
The source’s direct contribution
Its relevance to HCOS™ Healthcare Instruments
Its principal evidence boundary
Evidence-to-Instrument Traceability
Evidence source	Direct contribution	Primary instrument connections	Key boundary
World Health Organization (2019)	Defines burn-out as an occupational phenomenon associated with chronic workplace stress that has not been successfully managed	"Human Load Check Instrument; Healthcare Systems Instrument"	"Classification source, not an intervention or instrument-validation study"
Maslach and Jackson (1981)	Establishes the multidimensional measurement structure underlying the Maslach Burnout Inventory	"Human Load Check Instrument; Annotated Evidence Instrument"	"Measures burnout dimensions; does not identify system causes or provide a clinical diagnosis"
Maslach and Leiter (2016)	"Synthesizes burnout as exhaustion, cynicism, and reduced efficacy and identifies six areas of worklife"	"Human Load Check; Policy and Metric Pressure; Healthcare Systems Instrument"	"Narrative synthesis; does not prove that a specific mismatch caused an individual outcome"
Edmondson (1999)	Defines team psychological safety and links it with team learning behaviors	"Healthcare Communication; Healthcare Technology and AI Review; Healthcare Systems Instrument"	"Did not study burnout, healthcare, or AI directly"
Maslach and Leiter (2017)	"Reviews the importance of the healthcare social environment, civility, and organizational approaches to burnout"	"Healthcare Communication; Human Load Check; Healthcare Systems Instrument"	"Civility should complement, not replace, structural reform"

AE-HC-001 — Burn-out as an Occupational Phenomenon
Citation
World Health Organization. (2019, May 28). Burn-out an “occupational phenomenon”: International Classification of Diseases. https://www.who.int/news/item/28-05-2019-burn-out-an-occupational-phenomenon-international-classification-of-diseases
Source Type
Authoritative international classification statement.
Direct Contribution
The World Health Organization describes burn-out in ICD-11 as a syndrome conceptualized as resulting from chronic workplace stress that has not been successfully managed. It identifies three dimensions:
Energy depletion or exhaustion
Increased mental distance, negativism, or cynicism related to work
Reduced professional efficacy
WHO classifies burn-out as an occupational phenomenon rather than a medical condition and limits the construct to the occupational context. WHO also clarifies that burn-out was present in ICD-10 within the same broad category, while ICD-11 provides a more detailed definition.
HCOS™ Instrument Relevance
This source supports the Human Load Check Instrument’s boundary against diagnosing a medical condition. It also supports directing attention toward the occupational environment when chronic workplace stress remains unresolved.
Within HCOS™, “not successfully managed” should not automatically be interpreted as individual failure. Occupational stress management may depend on workload, workflow, resources, authority, leadership decisions, recovery opportunities, and wider organizational conditions.
Evidence Boundary
This classification does not identify the cause of burn-out in a particular person, prescribe a measurement tool, establish diagnostic thresholds, or prove that a particular intervention will work. It also does not exclude the possibility that a person may have a coexisting medical or mental health condition requiring appropriate assessment.
AE-HC-002 — Measurement of Experienced Burnout
Citation
Maslach, C., & Jackson, S. E. (1981). The measurement of experienced burnout. Journal of Occupational Behaviour, 2(2), 99–113. https://doi.org/10.1002/job.4030020205
Source Type
Psychometric instrument-development study.
Direct Contribution
Maslach and Jackson (1981) developed and evaluated a multidimensional measure of experienced burnout. The work supported three related dimensions commonly described as emotional exhaustion, depersonalization, and personal accomplishment.
HCOS™ Instrument Relevance
The article helps distinguish a human outcome measure from a system diagnostic. Within HCOS™:
Emotional exhaustion may indicate depletion.
Depersonalization may reflect relational distancing or defensive adaptation.
Reduced personal accomplishment may reflect blocked efficacy or diminished ability to experience meaningful contribution.
These are interpretive possibilities, not automatic conclusions about cause.
Evidence Boundary
The Maslach Burnout Inventory does not independently diagnose a medical or psychiatric condition, identify which workplace factor caused a score, or determine the appropriate intervention. HCOS™ instruments should not reproduce proprietary inventory items or scoring instructions without appropriate authorization and licensing.
AE-HC-003 — Burnout and the Six Areas of Worklife
Citation
Maslach, C., & Leiter, M. P. (2016). Understanding the burnout experience: Recent research and its implications for psychiatry. World Psychiatry, 15(2), 103–111. https://doi.org/10.1002/wps.20311
Source Type
Narrative review and conceptual synthesis.
Direct Contribution
Maslach and Leiter (2016) describe burnout as an occupational syndrome involving exhaustion, cynicism, and reduced professional efficacy. They identify six areas of worklife in which persistent mismatches may contribute to burnout:
Workload
Control
Reward
Community
Fairness
Values
The authors emphasize changing workplace conditions rather than relying exclusively on individual coping strategies.
HCOS™ Instrument Relevance
The six areas provide an evidence-informed structure for examining:
Whether demand exceeds sustainable capacity
Whether responsibility is paired with meaningful authority
Whether effort is recognized and reciprocated
Whether relationships support trust and belonging
Whether burdens and decisions are distributed fairly
Whether organizational demands conflict with professional or ethical values
This source directly informs the Human Load Check Instrument and the Policy and Metric Pressure Instrument.
Evidence Boundary
The article does not establish that all six mismatches must be present, that any one mismatch caused burnout in a particular individual, or that individual support has no value. Workplace redesign and human support may both be necessary.
AE-HC-004 — Psychological Safety and Learning Behavior
Citation
Edmondson, A. C. (1999). Psychological safety and learning behavior in work teams. Administrative Science Quarterly, 44(2), 350–383. https://doi.org/10.2307/2666999
Source Type
Multimethod organizational field study.
Direct Contribution
Edmondson (1999) defines team psychological safety as a shared belief that the team is safe for interpersonal risk-taking. Psychological safety was associated with learning behaviors such as asking questions, seeking feedback, discussing errors, experimenting, and requesting help.
HCOS™ Instrument Relevance
This study supports designing instruments and implementation processes that make it easier for people to:
Admit uncertainty
Report errors
Request assistance
Challenge assumptions
Raise concerns
Participate in collective learning
For healthcare technology and AI, HCOS™ extends this logic to contestability, escalation, and the ability to question or override a technology-supported recommendation.
Evidence Boundary
The original study did not measure burnout and was not conducted as a healthcare or AI-governance study. Its application to burnout prevention, clinical environments, and AI oversight is a reasoned extension that requires context-specific evidence and evaluation.
Psychological safety also cannot compensate indefinitely for inadequate staffing, excessive workload, insufficient resources, or organizational unwillingness to act.
AE-HC-005 — Civility, Social Environment, and Burnout
Citation
Maslach, C., & Leiter, M. P. (2017). New insights into burnout and health care: Strategies for improving civility and alleviating burnout. Medical Teacher, 39(2), 160–163. https://doi.org/10.1080/0142159X.2016.1248918
Source Type
Narrative review and conceptual overview focused on healthcare and medical education.
Direct Contribution
Maslach and Leiter emphasize the importance of the social environment in healthcare and discuss workplace civility as a potentially modifiable organizational condition. The article considers how respectful social encounters and civility-focused interventions may contribute to reductions in burnout.
HCOS™ Instrument Relevance
This source supports attention to relational human load within the Healthcare Communication Instrument and Healthcare Systems Instrument. Incivility can add vigilance, conflict-management burden, interpersonal anxiety, and reluctance to seek help.
Civility may strengthen community, trust, belonging, communication, and access to support.
Evidence Boundary
Civility should not be treated as a substitute for adequate staffing, manageable workload, fair procedures, sufficient resources, appropriate authority, or recovery time. A respectful culture can reduce relational harm, but it cannot make structurally unsafe work sustainable.
Cross-Evidence HCOS™ Synthesis
Together, these sources support a layered approach:
1. Recognize the Human Outcome
Burnout-related experiences may involve exhaustion, distancing or cynicism, and reduced efficacy.
2. Preserve the Occupational Boundary
Burn-out is specifically situated in the occupational context and should not be used as a universal label for distress in every area of life.
3. Investigate the Work System
Potential system domains include workload, control, reward, community, fairness, values, leadership decisions, workflow, resources, and recovery time.
4. Protect Voice and Learning
People need conditions in which they can ask for help, discuss errors, report pressure, and challenge unsafe assumptions.
5. Address Relational and Structural Conditions
Civility and psychological safety are meaningful protections, but they must be accompanied by action on structural sources of pressure.
6. Avoid Diagnostic Overreach
HCOS™ instruments may support recognition, reflection, and structured review. They do not diagnose burnout or another health condition.
7. Keep Evidence and Interpretation Separate
Instrument outputs should identify whether a statement represents:
A direct research finding
An author interpretation
An HCOS™ synthesis
A hypothesis requiring testing
A proposed application
An unresolved question
